https://www.mathworks.com/help/wavelet/ug/time-frequency-convolutional-network-for-eeg-data-classification.html

how it works in that example:
The raw EEG time series are fed into the network as 1-D sequences. 
A continuous wavelet transform layer (cwtLayer) computes a scalogram (i.e., a time-frequency map). This produces 2D time-frequency maps for each input signal. 
After the scalogram layer, the network uses 2-D convolution and pooling layers — essentially treating the scalogram outputs like images (because they have time and frequency dimensions). 

So they don’t save or use external image files, but they do transform the 1-D signal into a 2-D time-frequency representation inside the network that functions similarly to an image for the 2-D convolutional layers.

